unless you want your team to keep the ball for minutes at a time, then counter in transition will probably help too

>>128881281
>because the description on positive
Don't believe what the tooltips say, they are wrong on many aspects of the game. What mentality does is managing risks, a more positive one tells your players to take more risks and vice versa. So if you want to counter you should actually be playing on Positive or Attacking, with a low block and the usual stuff. This tells your players to make those risky passes and offer more runs into space. Whereas, if you want possession you have to play Balanced or Positive, so they don't make many risky passes. If you play Cautious this affects your pressing too much, so you don't want that if you press high.

For the next rule cycle (starting with the 2026 season) I would:

- The cars themselves should be uprated WRC2/R2 with only a slightly more aero, and opened up turbo restrictors, to end up with 100-125 more hp. Low downforce high power cars
- Possibility for a manufacturer to be able to basically make 3 rally cars (R1-2-3) from the same base
- These regs would bring Skoda and Citroen back to the top category so thats already more publicity they bring with themselves
- Also brings back privateers to the top category

- Have an allstars event

You should check out Finite and Infinite Games by James Carse; its premise is that all games are either finite (where the goal is to end the game) or infinite (where the goal is to keep the game going).

What you're saying applies for anything in life that's a finite game (sport, warfare, politics). But in the infinite games (culture, art, expression, social life) there is room for individuality and creative expression. Sure, a musician might be more talented than another, in that he is able to pull off virtuosic performances on an instrument, but maybe the artist who isn't capable of such virtuosity chooses to express himself in a different manner altogether which crystallizes into a unique style, and allows him to connect with others in a more meaningful way.

Countries like Brazil have a very large population, a decent sports infrastructure, and tons of people willing to go for a pro career. One reason for France being this good recently is that they managed to import a few millions of relatively poor people who are willing to go for it. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128865113
Pot the 9 ball to win the rack
Object ball is the lowest numbered ball on the table
Have to either pot or hit a rail after contact with object ball
Fouls give opponent ball in hand
Plants are allowed, e.g. hitting the 1 but potting the 9 wins the rack
Only weird rule is the push out after the break, you can nominate to "push out" after the break (either player, so long as it's the first shot after the break), which allows you to hit the cue ball but without having to hit the object ball or a rail. Your opponent can then decide whether to play or put you back in after the push out.

>>128884159
Ploy is her real nick name (given since birth) In Thailand snooker circle. we call snooker players by alias name, usually it's nickname + place of their origin.
We call Mink= Mink Saraburi, Ploychompoo = Ploy Khon Kaen, Noppon = Moo Paknam, Siripaporn = Baipad Sriracha, Theppy = F Nakornnayok . All of these names are their real nickname+ their hometown

It has been kinda a snooker gambler tradition since many decades ago tho. (most snooker players come from gambling circle. they makes a living by gambling money so they have to go from city to city)

posts.com:
Djokovic is supremely talented. It's like someone created a cyberpunk tier cyborg and programmed it to play god level tennis. His game is ruthlessly efficient and precise, and he never seems to miss or make errors.

But much like watching a robot play chess, it's just not that entertaining. It's effective, devastating, and supremely impressive, but it's not exactly a fun watch.

Rafa was always a more physical player, which makes his shots way more exciting from an audience perspective. And Roger was always the pinnacle of grace and elegance on the court, his game was extremely aesthetic in general. But Djokovic is just like this tennis robot who never misses and calculates every single detail of how to win each point perfectly, then executes. He's not very aesthetic or powerful in his shots, he's just ruthlessly efficient. He doesn't make mistakes, and once he gets a break you know exactly how the rest of the set is going to play out. As far as the aesthetics of his game go, they just aren't that flashy or showy. There's absolutely nothing wrong with that from a player's point of view, but it does make him a lot less fun to actually watch compared to his two rivals.
